<body>
	<div class="banner">
		<center><font color="white" size="16px" face="arial">SdiA</font></center>
	</div>
	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">SdiA transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>of Salmonella enterica Is a LuxR Homolog Mixed Microbial Communities SdiA That Detects BINDHU MICHAEL ,1 JENEE N. SMITH ,1 SIMON SWIFT ,2 † FRED HEFFRON ,3 AND BRIAN M. M. AHMER1 * Department of Microbiology , The Ohio State University , Columbus , Ohio 43210-12921 ; Institute of Infections and Immunity , University of Nottingham , Queen 's Medical Centre , Nottingham NG7 2UH , United Kingdom2 ; and Department of Molecular Microbiology and Immunology , Oregon Health Sciences University , Portland , Oregon 97201-30983 Received 13 April 2001/Accepted 19 June 2001 Proteins of the LuxR family detect the presence of N-acylhomoserine lactones ( AHLs ) and regulate transcription accordingly .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Volf , J. , Sevcik , M. , Havlickova , H. , Sisak , F. , Damborsky , J. , and Rychlik , I. ( 2002 ) Role of SdiA in Salmonella enterica serovar Typhimurium physiology and virulence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20015147" target="_blank">20015147</a>]<br></li>
<li>Further upstream are two promoters , one of which is dependent on RpoS ( which is in turn positively regulated by RprA , an RcsB-dependent gene ) , and negatively regulated by SdiA , a LuxRlike regulator that apparently responds to homoserine lactone quorum signals ; another is positively regulated by SdiA ( 3 , 90 , 113 , 117 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16153174" target="_blank">16153174</a>]<br></li>
<li>If so , induction of ftnA by SdiA in response to rivals may allow greater sequestration of iron for anticompetition purposes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20015147" target="_blank">20015147</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of ftnA -- lacZ in the sdiA mutant was reduced further by the presence of Dip ( Fig. 4C ) , indicating that although ftnA expression is SdiA dependent , in the absence of SdiA , ftnA expression remains iron dependent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20015147" target="_blank">20015147</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the sdiA mutant , FtnA levels were still further reduced by growth under irondepleted conditions ( Fig. 4D ) , again suggesting that SdiA is not involved in the iron-responsive regulation of ftnA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20015147" target="_blank">20015147</a>]<br></li>
<li>The latter proteins are MalT , SdiA , and FimZ of E. coli , GerE of B. subtiIis , LuxR of Vibrio fischeri , ' and AlkS of Pseudomonas oleovorans ( Fig. 7 , Table 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7699720" target="_blank">7699720</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the upstream protection between 249 and 233 on the coding strand was enhanced , giving clearer protection , in the presence of SdiA ( Fig. 5A , lanes 2 -- 5 and 7 -- 10 ; and Fig. 5B , lanes 2 -- 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>As summarized in Fig. 9 , DNase I hypersensitive sites at 247 and 237 were observed in the presence of SdiA alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>244 on the non-coding strand ( Fig. 5B , lane 8 ) were observed with Es alone , but disappeared in the 70 presence of both Es and SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>The level of hypersensi-D tivity produced by SdiA alone at 237 on the coding strand ( see Fig. 4 ) also decreased in the presence of Es .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is possible that SdiA and YdiV synergistically regulate the intracellular concentration of cAMP to control QS system 2 in E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of ydiV is stimulated by the AHL-SdiA complex , and it contributes to the control of intracellular cAMP concentration , which leads to the inhibition of QS system 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>One is SdiA , which E binds to the promoter region of the ydiV gene and E positively regulates its transcription in response to extracellular autoinducer 1 from other bacterial species ( Zhou et al. , 2008 ; Dyszel et al. , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22461489" target="_blank">22461489</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA binds to the ydiV promoter region in a dose-dependent , but nonspecific , manner ; extracellular autoinducer 1 from other species stimulates ydiV expression in an sdiA-depen-dent manner .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>In summary , extracellular AI-1 causes more intense binding of SdiA to the ydiV promoter region , and it up-regulates ydiV expression in an sdiA-dependent manner .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , in contrast to the V. ﬁscheri LuxR system , in which LuxR regulates its own expression in the presence of OHHL , the SdiA protein is not required for the effect of the E. coli extracellular factor on sdiA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631660" target="_blank">8631660</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several AHLs generated by other microbial species activate SdiA of E. coli and S. typhimurium by binding and changing its conformation [ 6-9 ] ; thus , if chromosomal sdiA up-regulates the expression of ydiV , the addition of AHL would elevate ydiV expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine if SdiA can respond to AI-2 production , the luminescence of the Prck-luxCDABE reporter ( pBA428 ) was measured during growth under these conditions ( in the absence of any exogenous AHL ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , this step was troublesome because the chromosomal transcriptional fusions respond to SdiA only under specific growth conditions [ 20 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20126629" target="_blank">20126629</a>]<br></li>
<li>The question arises whether these loci ever respond to SdiA and AHL in nature .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results show that , whether or not AHL is present , SdiA binds DNA nonspecifically , at least in vitro in our experimental conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was also reported that SdiA responds to an unidentiﬁed compound present in spent E. coli culture supernatants ( 43 ) , although this effect was later explained by growth rate differences in fresh medium compared to spent medium ( 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA also does not respond to AI-2 or any other molecule present in its own culture supernatant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , if we assume that E. coli produces its own autoinducer to which SdiA responds , it is reasonable to suggest that the basal level of transcription from the SdiA-dependent promoter would be lower in the absence of the endogenous signal molecule .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8552633" target="_blank">8552633</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , this SdiA box is not present in the promoters of any SdiA-regulated genes of Salmonella , including the Salmonella srgE-lux fusion that was placed into E. coli K-12 and was activated in an sdiA-dependent and AHL-dependent manner [ 5 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was later demonstrated that E. coli SdiA activates ftsQ in response to AHL ( 43 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , in E. coli K-12 and EHEC , SdiA is partially active even in the absence of AHL .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20126629" target="_blank">20126629</a>]<br></li>
<li>For instance , the expression of acrAB in E. coli is controlled by repressor protein AcrR , global activator protein MarA , SoxS , Rob and quorum sensing regulator LuxR homologue protein SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulation via the highly conserved SdiA homologue of S. enterica was recently found to respond to AHL , the most active of which was N - ( - ketocaproyl ) - L-homoserine lactone ( 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA may act to sense and respond to quorum-signalling molecules produced by other bacterial species ( Ahmer , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20015147" target="_blank">20015147</a>]<br></li>
<li>Escherichia coli produces no homoserine lactones of its own but can respond to homoserine lactones with the LuxR homologue SdiA ( Ahmer , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17064377" target="_blank">17064377</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the mre aph and mrdB aph alleles were all detrimental to survival , but viability was enhanced by increased SdiA activity in all cases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17993535" target="_blank">17993535</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , as SdiA activates bioﬁlm formation ( 38 ) , CsrA-mediated repression of SdiA synthesis would inhibit the process .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908661" target="_blank">21908661</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , CsrA-mediated repression of SdiA synthesis would reduce transcription of the CsrA antagonists CsrB and CsrC , leading to increased CsrA activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908661" target="_blank">21908661</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mixtures of two DNA fragments and increasing amounts of SdiA protein were incubated for 10 min at 378C and then subjected to 6 % PAGE in the absence of protein denaturants .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA protein used was : lane 1 , 0 pmol ; lane 2 , 0.1 pmol ; lane 3 , 0.2 pmol ; lane 4 , 0.4 pmol ; lane 5 , 0.7 pmol ; lane 6 , 1.4 pmol ; lane 7 , 2.8 pmol ; lane 8 , 5.6 pmol ; and lane 9 , 11.2 pmol .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>The amounts of SdiA protein added were : ( A ) lanes 2 and 7 , 11 pmol ; lanes 3 and 8 , 23 pmol ; lanes 4 and 9 , 45 pmol ; lanes 5 and 10 , 90 pmol ; ( B ) lane 2 , 11 pmol ; lane 3 , 23 pmol ; lane 4 , 45 pmol ; lane 5 , 90 pmol ; ( C ) lanes 2 and 11 , 0 pmol ; lanes 3 and 12 , 20 pmol ; lanes 4 and 13 , 45 pmol ; lanes 5 and 14 , 90 pmol .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this case increased levels of SdiA would not restore division activity to strains lacking the FtsZ protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1915297" target="_blank">1915297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of sdiA from pSC101-based vectors results in SdiA activity in the absence of ligand .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results further corroborate the previously stated hypothesis that SdiA has very low levels of activity in the absence of AHL and that the addition of AHL leads to a more stable folded protein [ 5 , 8 , 35 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>When sdiA is expressed from a plasmid , the concentration of the SdiA monomer is elevated and there is a corresponding increase in the equilibrium concentration of the dimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>These conditions might remove barriers to individual target gene expression , or may increase SdiA expression or activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20126629" target="_blank">20126629</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results demonstrate that increased gene dosage of sdiA , and-by implication-increased levels of the SdiA protein lead to an increase in the cellular concentration of FtsZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1915297" target="_blank">1915297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Instead , the overexpression are explained by the ability of SdiA to increase transcription of the ftsQAZ gene cluster , thereby increasing the cellular concentration of the FstZ protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1915297" target="_blank">1915297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upon reaching a quorum ( 46 ) , when the concentration of the proposed freely diffusible factors inside the cell reaches some threshold , SdiA and os respond by induction of ftsQA transcription from theP1 and P2 promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8552633" target="_blank">8552633</a>]<br></li>
<li>This induction could be either the result of direct interactions of SdiA and o-S with the ftsQA promoters or mediated through activation of other stimulatory factors .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8552633" target="_blank">8552633</a>]<br></li>
<li>Roles of aCTD and sCTD on transcription activation by SdiA In many cases , class I transcription factors bind upstream from promoter 235 and interact with aCTD for transcription activation or repression , whereas class II factors bind at the promoter 235 region and interact with sCTD ( for reviews , see Ishihama , 1993 ; 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>The D ftsQ P2 promoter is activated in vivo after overexpression of SdiA ( Wang et al. , 1991 ; Garcia-Lara et al. , 1996 ; Sitnikov et al. , 1996 ) , suggesting the involvement of SdiA in transcription activation from the P2 promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>The activation of ftsQ P2 by SdiA was observed in vivo after overexpression of SdiA ( Wang et al. , 1991 ; Sitnikov et al. , 1996 ) , but the repression of ftsQ P1 has not been reported .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Results Transcription activation of ftsQ P2 and repression of ftsQ P1 by SdiA Transcription of ftsQ is under the control of two promoters , upstream P2 and downstream P1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA activates transcription from ftsQ P2 in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Discussion Activation of P2 transcription and repression of P1 transcription by SdiA ( Es529 ) ( see Fig. 6 ) , but is not activated by SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription level represents the ratio of ftsQ P2 transcript in the presence of SdiA to that in its absence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ftsQ P1 transcripts were measured as above , and the relative levels of P1 transcripts are shown in the presence and absence of SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>This ﬁnding indicates that SdiA represses the binding of RNA polymerase to the ftsQ P1 promoter in the absence of strong binding of SdiA to the P2 region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>When wild-type RNA polymerase ( Es ) was used , ftsQ P2 transcription was activated D 3.5-fold by the addition of SdiA ( Fig. 6A , lanes 1 and 2 ; Fig. 6B , WT lane ) but , on the contrary , ftsQ P1 transcription was repressed to 20 % of the control level in the absence of SdiA ( Fig. 6A , lanes 1 and 2 ; Fig. 6C , WT lane ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>As CsrA has never been shown to control gene expression by binding exclusively to the coding sequence of a target transcript and , as found previously , SdiA indirectly activates transcription of csrB , experiments were performed to determine whether CsrA regulated sdiA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908661" target="_blank">21908661</a>]<br></li>
<li>The BarA sensor kinase and the DNA binding protein SdiA also regulate csrB transcription , apparently through effects on UvrY phosphorylation and uvrY expression , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA activates the expression of uvrY and , to a lesser extent , that of csrB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>Next , we performed the transcription assay in the presence of SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA may directly activate transcription of the srgC gene in S. typhimurium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since small amounts of the ftsQA gene products are required by the cell , the level of activation by SdiA may also be relatively low compared with activation of lux transcription by LuxR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8552633" target="_blank">8552633</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">SdiA protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>It will be interesting to determine if E. coli SdiA becomes active in a similar situation and to determine if any of the potential SdiA regulon members like acrAB and ftsQAZ become responsive to chromosomal sdiA in this setting .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20126629" target="_blank">20126629</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test the hypothesis that SdiA does not detect signals emanating from the same species that contain sdiA , representatives of these three genera were tested for activation of the pBA428 reporter using the cross-streak assay ( on an LB plate at 37 ° C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>By deﬁnition , D therefore , SdiA can be classiﬁed as a class II ( s contact ) transcription factor , at least in transcription-activation of the ftsQ P2 promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>To examine the mechanism of activation of ftsQ P2 transcription by SdiA , we carried out single-round transcription in vitro using reconstituted D S RNA polymerase holoenzymes , Es and Es .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>To examine which transcription factor contact domain , aCTD or sCTD , is required for transcription-activation by SdiA , we carried out in vitro transcription of ftsQ P1P2 promoters using the reconstituted RNA polymerase holoenzymes containing the mutant a-subunit ( a235 ) truncated at amino acid residue 235 ( Igarashi and Ishihama , 1991 ) or the mutant D s - subunit ( s529 ) truncated downstream from residue 529 ( Kumar et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>The 62 most Cterminal amino acid residues show 47-52 % homology to the domain containing the helix-turn-helix motif in DegU and GerE ( Bacillus subtilis ) , NarL and SdiA ( E. coli ) and RhlR ( Pseudomonas aeruginosa ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8817489" target="_blank">8817489</a>]<br></li>
<li>NarL , FimZ , UhpA and RcsB of subgroup ( c ) also certainly fall into the category of response regulator from the existence of phosphoryl-ation domain , although SdiA and MalT show the similarity to the above four regulatory proteins only in the C-terminal region containing the helix-turn-helix motif .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8729576" target="_blank">8729576</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA is a LuxR homologue that possesses a putative AHL binding domain and a second domain for binding DNA ( 54 , 56 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA facilitates the binding of RNA polymerase to the ftsQP2 promoter and requires an intact - subunit C-terminal domain for this effect ( 62 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">SdiA evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>The 62 most Cterminal amino acid residues show 47-52 % homology to the domain containing the helix-turn-helix motif in DegU and GerE ( Bacillus subtilis ) , NarL and SdiA ( E. coli ) and RhlR ( Pseudomonas aeruginosa ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8817489" target="_blank">8817489</a>]<br></li>
<li>NarL , FimZ , UhpA and RcsB of subgroup ( c ) also certainly fall into the category of response regulator from the existence of phosphoryl-ation domain , although SdiA and MalT show the similarity to the above four regulatory proteins only in the C-terminal region containing the helix-turn-helix motif .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8729576" target="_blank">8729576</a>]<br></li>
<li>References Ahmer , B.M.M. , van Reeuwijk , J. , Timmers , C.D. , Valentine , P.J. , and Heffron , F. ( 1998 ) Salmonella typhimurium encodes an SdiA homolog , a putative quorum sensor of the LuxR family , that regulates genes on the virulence plasmid .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA is a member of the LuxR family of proteins , which regulate quorum sensing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA is a member of the quorum-sensing LuxR family of transcriptional regulators and has been shown to positively regulate cell division by speciﬁc trans-activa-tion of transcription of the ftsQAZ region , acting on the ftsQ2p promoter [ 46 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9614967" target="_blank">9614967</a>]<br></li>
<li>A 4.4-kb fragment encoding the S. typhimurium sdiA gene was sequenced and found to encode the 3 * end of YecC ( homologous to amino acid transporters of the ABC family ) , all of SdiA and SirA ( Salmonella invasion regulator ) , and the 5 * end of UvrC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9495757" target="_blank">9495757</a>]<br></li>
<li>SdiA is 69 % identical at the amino acid level to its E. coli homolog , while it is 26 % identical and 47 % similar to LuxR of V. ﬁscheri ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9495757" target="_blank">9495757</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among the R proteins identiﬁed so far , the PhzR protein of P. aureofaciens shows the highest homology to SdiA ( 28 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631660" target="_blank">8631660</a>]<br></li>
<li>Sequence similarities of sdiA to other transcriptional regulatory proteins The carboxy-terminal portion of SdiA showed significant sequence similarity to several other bacterial proteins that are positive regulators of gene expression ( Figure 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1915297" target="_blank">1915297</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , they possess the SdiA protein , which is homologous to the transcriptional regulators of the bacteria interacting with AHLs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17025177" target="_blank">17025177</a>]<br></li>
