			<label class="collapse_SIT" for="_5"><font size="5px">SdiA binding site</font></label>
				<input id="_5" type="checkbox">
				<div class="SIT"><br><ul><li>The environmental signal that SdiA recognizes is unknown , although sequence homology and evidence in E. coli ( 53 ) suggest that SdiA is a quorum sensor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9495757" target="_blank">9495757</a>]<br></li>
<li>Sequence alignment of S. typhimurium SdiA , E. coli SdiA , V. ﬁscheri LuxR , and P. aeruginosa LasR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9495757" target="_blank">9495757</a>]<br></li>
<li>Search for genes containing the SdiA box The DNA target of V. ﬁscheri LuxR protein is a 20 bp inverted-repeat , ACCTGTAGGA/TCGTACAGGT ( Devine et al. , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>bThe boxed-in sequences represent the potential SdiA box .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>A DNA fragment ( 73 bp from +112 to +184 with respect to the ftsQP2 initiation site ) formed complexes with SdiA as shown by the gel shift assay , but clear protection was not observed in this region as shown by DNase I footprinting , and there was no homolog of SdiA box present in this DNA fragment [ 11 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>For comparison , V. ﬁscheri LuxR , which binds to the lux box centred at 242.5 ( a half turn upstream from the SdiA box on ftsQ P2 ) from the luxI transcription start site ( Devine et al. , 1989 ; Fuqua et al. , 1994 ) , depends on aCTD for co-operative binding to the promoter with RNA polymerase and transcription activation ( Stevens et al. , 1994 ; 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>There is an inverted-repeat upstream of the P2 promoter , suggesting that this repeat could be a binding site for SdiA ( see Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8552633" target="_blank">8552633</a>]<br></li>
<li>A binding site for SdiA was demonstrated within the 35 region of the ftsQ promoter of E. coli , and the sequence 5 - AAAAG NNNNNNNNGAAAA-3 was reported to comprise an SdiA box .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study , we have determined for the ﬁrst time the SdiA binding site within the ftsQ promoter region , in which a sequence , 50-AAAAGNNNNNNNNGAAAA-30 , was identiﬁed ( this sequence is hereafter designated as the SdiA box ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>3 ′ was identified as the SdiA binding site within the ftsQ promoter region , which is hereafter designated as the SdiA box [ 11 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
				</ul></div><br>
			<label class="collapse_TU" for="_6"><font size="5px">Transcription unit regulated by SdiA</font></label>
				<input id="_6" type="checkbox">
				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>( A and B ) Expression from csrA-lacZ in KSA712 and SA KSA712 ( sdiA : : kanR ) ( A ) and KSA712 [ pBR322 ] and KSA712 [ pSdiA ] ( B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is noteworthy that three genes , pheP , pheA and aroF , involved in phenylalanine metabolism contain the SdiA box upstream from the respective translation initiation codons .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was later demonstrated that E. coli SdiA activates ftsQ in response to AHL ( 43 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11544237" target="_blank">11544237</a>]<br></li>
<li>As expected from the in vivo studies , D transcription of ftsQ P2 by Es was enhanced by the addition of SdiA , whereas in the same reaction , transcription of ftsQ P1 was repressed ( Fig. 1B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>When wild-type RNA polymerase ( Es ) was used , ftsQ P2 transcription was activated D 3.5-fold by the addition of SdiA ( Fig. 6A , lanes 1 and 2 ; Fig. 6B , WT lane ) but , on the contrary , ftsQ P1 transcription was repressed to 20 % of the control level in the absence of SdiA ( Fig. 6A , lanes 1 and 2 ; Fig. 6C , WT lane ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription from ftsQ P1 was signiﬁcantly reduced ( twofold ) by the addition of SdiA ( Fig. 6C , s 529 lane ) , D indicating that the sCTD is not involved in P1 repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Results Transcription activation of ftsQ P2 and repression of ftsQ P1 by SdiA Transcription of ftsQ is under the control of two promoters , upstream P2 and downstream P1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription from ftsQ P1 was found to be repressed by SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this system , one promoter is controlled by the speciﬁc activator SdiA , while the other promoter is stationary phase induced and sS dependent but not SdiA dependent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11133959" target="_blank">11133959</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sta-tionary-phase sigma factor RpoS and the LuxR family protein SdiA regulate the expression of the last genes in the dcw cluster , ftsQA and possibly ftsZ ( 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659771" target="_blank">24659771</a>]<br></li>
<li>The SdiA protein is the first factor thus far described that can regulate the division process by activating transcription of essential cell division genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1915297" target="_blank">1915297</a>]<br></li>
<li>Acid repressed genes encoding two activators of csrA , UvrY and LuxR-homolog SdiA [ 79 ] but up-regulated an IG that includes an antagonist of csrA , the sRNA csrB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17026754" target="_blank">17026754</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , it will be of interest to determine the in vivo situation in which the gad genes and fliE are regulated by SdiA and play a role in the bacterium 's fitness .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20126629" target="_blank">20126629</a>]<br></li>
<li>One possibility is that the genes regulated by SdiA are also under the control of another regulatory protein ( s ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9495757" target="_blank">9495757</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is possible that theftsQA genes are not the only target of SdiA and that other genes might be regulated by this transcriptional activator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8552633" target="_blank">8552633</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of ftnA -- lacZ in the sdiA mutant was reduced further by the presence of Dip ( Fig. 4C ) , indicating that although ftnA expression is SdiA dependent , in the absence of SdiA , ftnA expression remains iron dependent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20015147" target="_blank">20015147</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the sdiA mutant , FtnA levels were still further reduced by growth under irondepleted conditions ( Fig. 4D ) , again suggesting that SdiA is not involved in the iron-responsive regulation of ftnA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20015147" target="_blank">20015147</a>]<br></li>
<li>The exact role of SdiA in E. coli is unclear as is the reason for its control of ftnA , as observed here .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20015147" target="_blank">20015147</a>]<br></li>
<li>The genes activated by sdiA suggest a role for SdiA in regulation of the glutamate dependent acid resistance system , AR-2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20126629" target="_blank">20126629</a>]<br></li>
<li>Introduction Summary SdiA , an Escherichia coli homologue of the quorumsensing regulator , controls the expression of the ftsQAZ operon for cell division .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>For instance , the expression of acrAB in E. coli is controlled by repressor protein AcrR , global activator protein MarA , SoxS , Rob and quorum sensing regulator LuxR homologue protein SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>Also , the quorum-sensing regulator SdiA controls the expression of acrAB , acrD , and acrEF ( 50 , 68 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716448" target="_blank">15716448</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore we conclude that ftsQAZ and acrAB are not part of the E. coli SdiA regulon under the conditions tested .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20126629" target="_blank">20126629</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , the environmental signal that permits SdiA of E. coli to regulate uvrY expression and , as a consequence , csrB transcription remains to be determined .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>Recently , Kanamaru et al. ( 2000 ) found that the expression of virulence factors , EspD and intimin encoded by the eae gene , was repressed by SdiA in E. coli O157 : H7 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of ydiV is stimulated by the AHL-SdiA complex , and it contributes to the control of intracellular cAMP concentration , which leads to the inhibition of QS system 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>No signiﬁcant effect of SdiA was observed for csrA - lacZ expression ( Fig. 7A and B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12193630" target="_blank">12193630</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , in contrast to the V. ﬁscheri LuxR system , in which LuxR regulates its own expression in the presence of OHHL , the SdiA protein is not required for the effect of the E. coli extracellular factor on sdiA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631660" target="_blank">8631660</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we found that SdiA , a LuxR homolog , and the EAL domain protein encoded by ydiV were also repressed at the transcriptional level by the addition of glucose and that the effect of glucose on ydiV expression was not mediated by SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>( A ) SdiA stimulates ydiV expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggest that glucose inhibits sdiA and ydiV expression and that the effect of glucose on ydiV expression is not mediated by SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18560382" target="_blank">18560382</a>]<br></li>
<li>As CsrA has never been shown to control gene expression by binding exclusively to the coding sequence of a target transcript and , as found previously , SdiA indirectly activates transcription of csrB , experiments were performed to determine whether CsrA regulated sdiA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908661" target="_blank">21908661</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of the correct conditions for expression by these other proteins , chromosomally encoded SdiA may not be able to activate the promoters , while overexpressed SdiA is able to effectively compete with these other inﬂuences and activate transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9495757" target="_blank">9495757</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this paper , we describe the mechanism of transcription regulation of the ftsQ gene by SdiA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11555297" target="_blank">11555297</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition to stimulating transcription of the ftsQAZ division genes ( 87 ) , SdiA affects the expression of many other genes as well ( 89 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17993535" target="_blank">17993535</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul></div><br>
	</div>
